<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the SINGLE `sp_widget` row that
    defines the CASE CONFIRMATION WIDGET of the unauthenticated Experience
    Portal inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`. This widget is the
    THIRD of the three Service Portal widgets required by AAP Section 0.4.4
    ("two unauthenticated pages: case submission and case status lookup") and
    AAP Section 0.5.1 (in-scope artifact list).

    PURPOSE (AAP Sections 0.1.1 / 0.4.4 / 0.7.4 / Validation Gate 4
    "Portal - submission"):

      AAP Section 0.4.4 verbatim ("UI Design - External Experience Portal UI"):
        "Page 1 - Case Submission: a simple form with five inputs (subject,
         type, description, requester_name, requester_email). On submit, calls
         the scripted REST endpoint, displays a confirmation panel showing the
         returned case number and a friendly 'Your case has been submitted'
         message."

      AAP Section 0.5.1 (in-scope artifact, resolved to concrete scope):
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/portal/sp_widget_x_casemgmt_case_confirmation_widget.xml -
         confirmation widget displaying returned case number"

      This widget renders, after a successful case submission, exactly two
      pieces of content:
        1. The verbatim friendly success message "Your case has been submitted"
           (capital "Y", lowercase elsewhere, NO trailing period - matching
           the AAP quote character-for-character).
        2. The auto-generated case number returned by the case submission REST
           endpoint (e.g., CASE0000001), passed in via the widget options.

      Validation Gate 4 ("Portal - submission") verbatim from AAP Section 0.7.3:
        "Case created from unauthenticated portal submission - Case appears in
         internal list with Draft status and correct case number."
      Although Gate 4's pass criterion focuses on the case being CREATED
      (which happens in the REST endpoint + Script Include), the user-facing
      confirmation is what makes the submission UX usable. This widget is the
      third leg of the submission tripod (form widget -> REST endpoint ->
      confirmation widget); without this widget, the submission widget would
      have no way to confirm success to the user.

    THE WIDGET IS A "LEAF" DISPLAY-ONLY COMPONENT:
      This widget has the simplest design contract of any in this scoped
      application:
        - NO client-side AJAX calls (no $http, no $resource, no fetch).
        - NO server-side database operations (no GlideRecord reads or writes).
        - NO state machine; no event listeners; no buttons.
        - The case number flows in via widget options, exposed to the template
          via c.options.number, and rendered as plain interpolated text.
      It is "embedded" by the case submission widget via the canonical
      ServiceNow Service Portal pattern of $sp.getWidget('id', { ... }) on
      the server side plus the <sp-widget widget="..."> directive on the
      template side. The submission widget sets c.data.confirmationWidget.
      options.number = String(response.data.number); after a successful POST
      to /api/x_casemgmt/case_submit, then conditionally renders this widget
      in place of the form via ng-if.

    UNAUTHENTICATED ANONYMOUS-ACCESS DESIGN (AAP Section 0.4.4 verbatim:
    "two unauthenticated pages"):
      Three configuration mechanisms work together to make this widget
      renderable by anonymous, unauthenticated callers (matching the parent
      submission widget's flags and the parent page's flags):

        1. <public>true</public> - explicit signal to the platform's
           authorization layer that THIS WIDGET is exempt from the standard
           authentication challenge.

        2. <internal>false</internal> - the widget is publicly accessible
           and NOT restricted to "internal" (employee-only) widgets.

        3. <roles/> - empty. No roles are required to render the widget.
           The Service Portal widget-level role-based gating is bypassed by
           the empty roles list, so any caller (including anonymous) who
           reaches the parent page can render the widget.

      All three mechanisms are necessary; omitting any one breaks the
      anonymous-access guarantee for the chained user journey:
        anonymous user -> portal record -> submission page -> submission
        widget -> (on submit success) -> THIS confirmation widget.

    DEFAULT THEME / NO CUSTOM CSS (AAP Section 0.4.4 verbatim: "Visual
    treatment: ServiceNow Experience Portal default theme. No custom CSS,
    no custom branding."):
      The <css> element is empty. All visual styling uses out-of-the-box
      Service Portal Bootstrap classes already shipped with the PDI:
        - alert alert-success: green-bordered success panel with subtle
          icon and standard padding.
        - <h3>: standard heading typography.
        - <strong>: bold emphasis on the case number for visual scanning.
      No custom CSS is authored or referenced. No custom branding artifacts
      (icons, images, colors) are defined.

    NO HARDCODED SYS_IDS IN REFERENCES (AAP Section 0.7.2):
      Every cross-reference is a name lookup against a stable identifier:
        - <sys_scope> resolves against the scope record's <name> field
          (`x_casemgmt`) per ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml.
        - <sys_package> resolves against the sys_app record's <scope> field
          (`x_casemgmt`) per ../../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml.
      The ONLY sys_id literal in this file is <sys_id> itself (THIS record's
      own primary key). It is the deterministic 32-char lowercase hex MD5
      of `sp_widget_x_casemgmt_case_confirmation_widget`:
        printf '%s' 'sp_widget_x_casemgmt_case_confirmation_widget' | md5sum | cut -c1-32
        -> a198a7f3386d6b0b146451dcfa3c2126
      Per AAP Section 0.7.2, the no-hardcoded-sys_id rule applies to
      references TO OTHER records, not to a record's own identity primary
      key.

    NO PII, NO EMAIL (AAP Sections 0.7.2, 0.3.2):
      The description and template below contain ZERO PII (no real names,
      no real email addresses, no real organization names, no real case
      numbers). Email notifications are explicitly disabled on the PDI per
      AAP Section 0.7.2 - this widget makes no notification calls
      (gs.eventQueue, NotificationService, etc.).

    `casemgmt` SCOPE IDENTIFIER (AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2):
      All `x_casemgmt_*` references use the concrete scope identifier
      `casemgmt` per AAP Section 0.7.2 ("Scoped-namespace-only constraint").
      ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser (Java
      DocumentBuilder); the scope identifier MUST be concrete in the XML
      before export. The same identifier is used consistently across every
      sibling XML in this scoped application (see sibling pages, REST
      endpoints, dashboards, reports, and seed records).

    XML CONVENTIONS HONORED (matching sibling files in this app):
      - Wrapper element: <record_update table="sp_widget"> per the agent
        prompt's Phase 1 specification, matching the sibling pattern used
        by ../sp_portal_x_casemgmt_case_portal.xml.
      - Indentation: 4 spaces for record fields (matching sibling-file
        convention).
      - Element ordering: alphabetical within the record (matching
        sibling-file convention).
      - sys_scope text-node value: `x_casemgmt` (matching the actual scope
        record's <name>).
      - sys_package text-node value: `x_casemgmt` with source="x_casemgmt"
        attribute (matching the sys_app record's <scope>).
      - Deterministic 32-char lowercase hex sys_id: computed as
        MD5("sp_widget_x_casemgmt_case_confirmation_widget") =
        a198a7f3386d6b0b146451dcfa3c2126. Re-generation of this XML is
        byte-identical (no random UUIDs).
      - Audit fields: <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by> and
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on> for stable
        repeatable timestamps (the same date is used by EVERY sibling
        record in this scoped app for repeatable XML re-generation).
      - No smart quotes, no leading/trailing whitespace, no BOM. Strict
        XML conformance for ServiceNow Update Set re-import preview
        (AAP Section 0.7.3 validation gate 7).

    SOURCE-SIDE SEMANTIC REFERENCE (read-only context, NOT byte-for-byte
    ported per AAP Section 0.5.1):

      acm-services/acm-service-portal-gateway/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
      portalgateway/service/DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService.java
        line 60-65 - submitRequest(...) implementation; resolves provider
                     by request type and forwards. Returns a PortalResponse
                     containing the confirmation identifier returned by the
                     downstream provider (in ArkCase: a request id; in this
                     ServiceNow target: the auto-generated case number).

      ArkCase's PortalResponse DTO carries the confirmation identifier
      returned by submitRequest(...). The ServiceNow target's confirmation
      widget consumes the equivalent identifier (the case number) and
      renders it. The semantic intent is preserved (display submission
      confirmation); the technology stack is restructured to fit
      ServiceNow's UI Builder/Service Portal conventions.

    CROSS-REFERENCES (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record; <sys_scope>
          cross-reference resolves against this record's <name>)
        - ../../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped
          application record; <sys_package> cross-reference resolves
          against this record's <scope>)

      THIS RECORD SHOULD LOAD BEFORE (but ServiceNow's two-pass import
      tolerates any order within the same Update Set, since references
      resolve by name):
        - ./sp_widget_x_casemgmt_case_submission_widget.xml (the submission
          widget embeds this widget via $sp.getWidget('x_casemgmt_case_
          confirmation_widget', { number: ... }))
        - ../pages/sp_page_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml (the page hosts the
          submission widget which transitively embeds this widget)

    VALIDATION-GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3 - the seven validation gates):
      This widget supports Validation Gate 4 ("Portal - submission") by
      providing the success-confirmation UI that the submission widget swaps
      in after a successful POST. Without this widget, the submission user
      experience would have no terminal success state.
-->
<record_update table="sp_widget">
    <sp_widget action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <category>custom</category>
        <client_script><![CDATA[function CaseConfirmationWidgetController($scope) {
    /*
     * Case Confirmation Widget - client-side controller.
     *
     * This widget is a pure display component. It receives the auto-generated
     * case number via widget options (set by the parent submission widget via
     * $sp.getWidget('x_casemgmt_case_confirmation_widget', { number: '...' })),
     * and exposes it to the template via c.options.number for interpolation.
     *
     * NO AJAX calls, NO event listeners, NO state machine, NO buttons - this
     * controller's sole responsibility is to expose the options object to the
     * template under the `c` alias and defensively coerce the number to a
     * string for predictable template binding.
     */
    var c = this;

    // Expose widget options to the template via c.options.
    // ServiceNow's Service Portal framework auto-populates $scope.options from
    // the widget instance options (set by the parent's $sp.getWidget call).
    // We assign it explicitly to c.options for `controller as c` syntax clarity.
    c.options = $scope.options || {};

    // Defensive coercion: ensure c.options.number is always a string (or empty
    // string) so the template's ng-if and {{}} interpolation behave predictably.
    // Handles edge cases where the parent passes a non-string value (e.g., a
    // number primitive, null, or undefined). Without this guard, the template
    // could render the literal text "null" or "undefined".
    if (c.options.number == null) {
        c.options.number = '';
    } else {
        c.options.number = String(c.options.number);
    }
}
]]></client_script>
        <controller_as>c</controller_as>
        <css/>
        <data_table>sp_instance</data_table>
        <description>Custom display-only Service Portal widget that shows the verbatim text 'Your case has been submitted' plus the auto-generated case number after a successful case submission. Embedded by sp_widget_x_casemgmt_case_submission_widget via $sp.getWidget(); receives the case number via the 'number' widget option (exposed to the template as c.options.number). Per AAP Section 0.4.4 (verbatim 'Your case has been submitted' message) and Validation Gate 4 (Portal - submission). No client-side AJAX, no server-side database operations - pure display component.</description>
        <docs/>
        <field_list/>
        <has_preview>false</has_preview>
        <id>x_casemgmt_case_confirmation_widget</id>
        <internal>false</internal>
        <link/>
        <name>Case Confirmation Widget</name>
        <option_schema>[{"name":"number","label":"Case Number","section":"Presentation","type":"string","default_value":""}]</option_schema>
        <pop_up>false</pop_up>
        <public>true</public>
        <roles/>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    /*
     * Case Confirmation Widget - server-side data initialization.
     *
     * No server-side data fetch is needed. The case number is passed via widget
     * options by the parent (case submission widget) after a successful POST to
     * /api/x_casemgmt/case_submit. The client-side controller exposes c.options
     * to the template, which interpolates {{c.options.number}}.
     *
     * This widget intentionally performs ZERO database operations:
     *   - No GlideRecord reads (no fetching of the freshly-created case row).
     *   - No GlideRecord writes (all writes happen through the scripted REST
     *     endpoint at sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit; this widget
     *     does not duplicate that contract).
     *   - No gs.eventQueue calls (email notifications are disabled per AAP
     *     Section 0.7.2 Email-disabled constraint).
     *
     * The IIFE pattern matches ServiceNow's standard widget server-script
     * convention; the empty body is the canonical no-op placeholder.
     */
})();
]]></script>
